As a natural consequence of the dHvA oscillations, we can determinate the area $S$ of the extremal cross-section of the Fermi surface of the atomic cloud through the Onsager-like relation

\begin{eqnarray}
S = \frac{2\pi N}{\hbar \rho} \nonumber
\end{eqnarray}

Using the physical parameters of the system we estimate the area of the Fermi circle in $ S \approx 5 \times 10^{53} \ m^{-2} $.





\section{Conclusion}

In conclusion, we have studied an atomic analog of the de Haas van Alphen effect based on the Aharonov-Casher interaction. From the Landau-Aharonov-Casher theory we have obtained the effective magnetic field as as well as the energy eigenfunctions and eigenvalues for a system composed by neutral particles trapped in 2D atomic gas. We have showed that the finite dimensions of the atomic cloud limit the magnetic field strength. Considered the particles as being $ ^{87}\mathrm{Rb}  $ ultracold Rydberg atoms we have calculated the LAC degeneracy. We have displayed quantum oscillations in the energy and effective magnetization as a function of the inverse of the AC magnetic field. We have estimated the area of the Fermi surface of the atomic gas.



